Hydroxide conductivity can be calculated from electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) and a two- or four-electrode testing cell [118]. After soaking an AEM in DI water overnight, the membrane is secured in the testing cell and varying AC current is applied to collect impedance data. Using nonlinear least squares regression analysis, the membrane ionic resistance (Rm) can be obtained and from that the conductivity (σ) can be calculated from the following [70, 119]:10σ=LRm∗A.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
